  "prompt": "If India was a part of UNSC would it have been able to ban Masood Azhar without China's support?",
  "response": "The United Nations Security Council (UNSC) operates on a system wherein significant decisions, especially those involving sanctions or designations of individuals as terrorists, require the consensus or at least the absence of a veto from any of the five permanent members (P5): the United States, the United Kingdom, France, Russia, and China.\n\nIn the case of designating someone like Masood Azhar as a terrorist by the UNSC, even if India were a permanent member, it would still require the agreement of at least the other four permanent members, including China. Each of the P5 members holds veto power, which means that any one of them can block substantive decisions. Therefore, China\u2019s support or at least its decision not to veto would still be necessary for such a designation to proceed.\n\nIn short, even with India as a member of the UNSC, achieving a ban on Masood Azhar without China's agreement would still be challenging due to the existing veto power dynamics.",
